WEBVTT

1
00:00:02.230 --> 00:00:06.360
Today, we are going to talk about the iceberg theory

2
00:00:06.400 --> 00:00:10.740
of anger. The iceberg is a really

3
00:00:10.780 --> 00:00:15.470
powerful metaphor that we can use to explain our anger.

4
00:00:17.160 --> 00:00:20.600
As you can see in the picture, about ten percent

5
00:00:20.640 --> 00:00:25.120
of the iceberg is above water. The other ninety

6
00:00:25.220 --> 00:00:30.040
percent lays below the waterline. We

7
00:00:30.140 --> 00:00:33.760
only see a small fraction of the iceberg, as most

8
00:00:33.840 --> 00:00:38.690
of it is hidden beneath the surface. Well,

9
00:00:38.800 --> 00:00:43.640
anger functions very much in a similar way. When

10
00:00:43.760 --> 00:00:48.420
we get angry, we show others our angry emotions, behavior,

11
00:00:48.740 --> 00:00:53.700
and actions. What others don't see are the deeper core

12
00:00:53.840 --> 00:00:58.769
feelings and thoughts hidden below the surface. For those

13
00:00:58.800 --> 00:01:02.980
who struggle with their anger, the ten percent appears to

14
00:01:03.020 --> 00:01:07.800
be the only emotion they know how to feel or

15
00:01:07.860 --> 00:01:12.640
are most comfortable expressing. Now, why would this be?

16
00:01:17.420 --> 00:01:21.140
Well, strange as it may seem, a lot of people

17
00:01:21.220 --> 00:01:26.040
cannot identify their f-- their feelings. They never learned

18
00:01:26.120 --> 00:01:30.830
about their feelings as children. The second answer

19
00:01:31.080 --> 00:01:35.420
to this question is a lot of people are only

20
00:01:35.500 --> 00:01:40.320
in tune with the three most basic feelings: anger,

21
00:01:40.780 --> 00:01:45.520
happiness, and sadness. But I think if we

22
00:01:45.640 --> 00:01:50.160
look more in depth at this question, there's perhaps something

23
00:01:50.300 --> 00:01:55.280
more complex going on. I think a lot of

24
00:01:55.320 --> 00:02:00.180
people have difficulty sharing their underlying feelings because in doing

25
00:02:00.360 --> 00:02:03.380
so, they become more vulnerable.

26
00:02:07.120 --> 00:02:10.220
Incidentally, when we look at the iceberg, it is often

27
00:02:10.229 --> 00:02:13.800
the ninety percent, the part of the iceberg under the

28
00:02:13.840 --> 00:02:18.300
water, that does the most damage. But let's back-- get

29
00:02:18.380 --> 00:02:22.700
back to anger and people. In certain

30
00:02:22.760 --> 00:02:27.540
relationships, we sometimes only show the top ten percent of

31
00:02:27.580 --> 00:02:31.900
our emotions and keep the most important feelings and thoughts

32
00:02:32.240 --> 00:02:35.920
hidden below the surface, the other ninety percent.

33
00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:42.260
This is when problems start to build up. Our partners

34
00:02:42.520 --> 00:02:46.090
and those close to us end up only seeing the

35
00:02:46.180 --> 00:02:50.780
behaviors above the water, and those behaviors can sometimes be

36
00:02:50.800 --> 00:02:53.280
destructive and drive them away.

37
00:02:59.920 --> 00:03:01.950
What are some of the core feelings that we hide

38
00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:05.160
below the surface that are difficult for us to share?

39
00:03:07.280 --> 00:03:11.880
Another way of asking this question is: What are the

40
00:03:12.080 --> 00:03:16.720
underlying feelings that we keep hidden from others because they

41
00:03:16.800 --> 00:03:21.260
are too raw? Well, how about abandonment,

42
00:03:21.920 --> 00:03:26.760
shame, embarrassment, fear, worry, rejection,

43
00:03:26.820 --> 00:03:31.160
disappointment, sadness, grief, depression, and maybe despair?

44
00:03:32.780 --> 00:03:37.760
How about hurt? Have you ever felt so

45
00:03:37.900 --> 00:03:40.840
hurt in your marriage that you felt it in your

46
00:03:40.980 --> 00:03:45.860
heart and your bones? Well,

47
00:03:46.220 --> 00:03:51.180
how do we change this? Well, very simply, the

48
00:03:51.240 --> 00:03:54.780
most important action that we can take in these situations

49
00:03:55.220 --> 00:03:59.600
is to turn the iceberg upside down and connect with

50
00:03:59.640 --> 00:04:03.660
the other ninety percent of feelings that we are experiencing.

51
00:04:05.120 --> 00:04:09.360
In other words, when you feel anger coming on, stop

52
00:04:09.400 --> 00:04:14.400
and ask the following questions. What's really going

53
00:04:14.480 --> 00:04:19.060
on with me? What am I really feeling? Do I

54
00:04:19.100 --> 00:04:23.380
feel hurt, s-sad, tired? Am I feeling

55
00:04:23.420 --> 00:04:27.720
misunderstood? Am I worried, depressed? Am I feeling fear,

56
00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:31.900
rejection? Do I feel abandoned? What is it?

57
00:04:33.420 --> 00:04:37.540
In essence, you are being invited to stop, pause,

58
00:04:38.320 --> 00:04:43.260
reflect, and think. By pausing and

59
00:04:43.300 --> 00:04:47.910
reflecting and connecting to our underlying emotions, the other ninety

60
00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:52.700
percent of the iceberg, we develop greater self-awareness and

61
00:04:52.740 --> 00:04:56.940
understanding about what we are feeling and experiencing.

62
00:04:59.180 --> 00:05:03.000
Better awareness of how we feel can lead to better

63
00:05:03.040 --> 00:05:07.900
communication if we are able to share these underlying feelings

64
00:05:07.940 --> 00:05:12.940
with someone whom we trust. So

65
00:05:14.340 --> 00:05:19.320
there you have it, the iceberg theory of feelings.

66
00:05:20.720 --> 00:05:24.460
So think of the last time you were angry. What

67
00:05:24.500 --> 00:05:28.080
were some of the underlying emotions that led you to

68
00:05:28.120 --> 00:05:33.060
feel that way? I'm Veronica Hislop, life

69
00:05:33.180 --> 00:05:37.490
relationship coach and counselor, coming to you with

70
00:05:37.560 --> 00:05:39.100
empowered solutions.
